body:
In this pull request:
- nltk/test/runtests.py script (which can run all nltk tests) is introduced;
- a patched version of nose doctest plugin is bundled;
- old doctest testrunner is removed as well as old bundled coverage.py script; excludes from this script are migrated to runtests.py script;
- IBModel1 tests are skipped by changing `>>>` to `>>` (I had no luck neither with exclude nor with # doctest + SKIP);
- pypy test running is fixed.

1. Faster HiddenMarkovModelTrainer.train_supervised (30-40x faster in demo_pos() example): HiddenMarkovModelTrainer._states and HiddenMarkovModelTrainer._symbols are lists so `if state not in self._states` and `if symbol not in self._symbols` are O(N). This is fixed by maintaining `known_symbols` and `known_states` sets.
2. more tests for HiddenMarkovModelTagger are added;
3. I think that probability calculations were incorrect for multiple observation sequences (they were not normalized);
4. when an initial model was passed to train_unsupervised the calculations were totally off because states and symbols of trainer and model was not the same - this is fixed; also, train_unsupervised didn't affect .tag if a model was used before (because of caching issues) - this is also fixed.

The patch will make the code match [the description of the Algorithm](https://github.com/snowballstem/snowball-website/blob/72a7277d8b9df089c7f5c162b41a0f456c2aa1ee/algorithms/portuguese/stemmer.html#L250-L257). This way, "execução" and "execuções" will have the same stem;
Similarly for "revolução" and "revoluções".

Follows up 986d10324d544df1bda41b822e8800ebf3126c1d.

@stevenbird I've made the changes discussed in https://github.com/nltk/nltk/pull/884. I think you'll find this version cleaner. 

With regards to lazy loading, I was under the impression that wrapping CrubadanCorpusReader in 
LazyCorpusLoader in corpus/**init**.py is all I needed; or did you mean I should modify the code to use nltk.data.LazyLoader in place of open() somehow? (I was only able to find an example in nltk/corpus/reader/plaintext.py)

- Update `customer_reviews_1` corpus name to `product_reviews_1`;
- add `product_reviews_2` corpus to `corpus/__init__.py`;
- refactor methods and functions in sentiment modules;
- add docstrings.

Fixes failures related to `twython` imports and backward compatibility:
- splits `twitter/util.py` functionalities in two modules (with and without `twython` dependencies);
- fixes some Python 2.6 compatibility problems (`.format()` syntax).

Basic implementation of a stack decoder.

This only implements the "engine" of translation. Some major components still need to be done before machine translation is viable: language model (that's a big one), extracting phrase tables from corpora, reading phrase tables generated by Moses, not loading the entire phrase table in memory.

@alvations If you have the time, I would appreciate it if you looked at the interface and see how it compares with your monotone decoder.

This PR fixes `nltk.stanford.parse` tests output.

@stevenbird I think the different output could be related to the new versions of the Stanford Parser. Or maybe the previous output was based on CoreNLP and not the standalone parser (see [Stanford Parser FAQ][1]). However, I would be grateful if you could please take a look at the new output and check whether it is correct.

[1]: http://nlp.stanford.edu/software/parser-faq.shtml#corenlpdiff

Old code causes this warning:
SyntaxWarning: "is not" with a literal. Did you mean `!=` ?
  if ret is not 0:

Builds on #2709 so plz merge that first.

@dannysepler take a look at `nltk/test/unit/lm/test_models.py`. I know you were interested in how to convert those tests to pytest.

@manujosephv I noticed that kneser-ney trigram model does not sum up to unity at the level of bigrams. However a bigram model does (I added it explicitly to the tests). This is as expected, right?
